  "texts": [
    "◁ Lemma 2.16 (Regular Opens and Classicality).",
    "If F = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩ is a partial-state frame in which every X ∈ P is a regular open set in O(S, ⊑), and if φ ∈ L(Φ, ∅) is a classical propositional tautology, then φ is valid over F; so by Fact 2.5.3, every substitution instance of φ in L(Φ, I) is valid over F.The perspectives of Remarks 2.13 and 2.15 come together easily in part 3 of the following fact.",
    "For part 2, let⇓X = {y ∈ S | ∃x ∈ X: y ⊑ x}, so ⇓X = X iff X is a downset.Fact 2.17 (Regular Opens, Persistence, and Refinability).",
    "For any poset ⟨S, ⊑⟩ and X ⊆ S:1. int(cl(X)) = {x ∈ S | ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃x ′′ ⊑ x ′: x ′′ ∈ X}; 2. int(cl(⇓X)) is the smallest regular open set that includes X;3.",
    "X satisfies persistence and refinability as in Remark 2.13 iff X is regular open in O(S, ⊑).Proof."
  ],
